<subSubSection pageId="148" pageNumber="149" type="names">
<paragraph pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">nee-par hsay-pin</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="148" pageNumber="149" type="range">
<paragraph pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="148" pageNumber="149">From India and Sri Lana to Malay Archipelago. In Myanmar, grows naturally in the hot zone and at the base of the Bago Yoma Hills.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="uses">
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
<pageBreakToken pageId="149" pageNumber="150" start="start">Uses</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Leaf</emphasis>
: Crushed and used as a poultice over sores; if the sore is newly formed, the inflammation will go down and if it is mature, it will come to a head, expel the pus and be cured. Boiled and taken to cure fever. The liquid from boiled leaves is mixed with mustard seeds and given to children suffering from dysentery. The leaves or the bark can be crushed and the resulting liquid applied to cure stiff and knotted muscles, swelling in the joints and in other painful areas. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Fruit</emphasis>
: Roasted, crushed with a moderate amount of salt, and used as a toothpaste, it will firm up gums and teeth. Pressing dried fruit powder to sores to stop bleeding. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Root</emphasis>
: Used in making laxatives.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
